04025nam a22006135i 9780271062563DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20152013pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710625637 a10.1515/97802710625632doi  a(DE-B1597)584497  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPHI0220002bisacsh04a297.122600999999971 aYazicioglu, Isra, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aUnderstanding the Qurʾanic Miracle Stories in the Modern Age /cIsra Yazicioglu. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2015] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSignifying (on) Scriptures ;v300tFrontmatter -- tcontents -- tAcknowledgments -- tNote on Transliteration -- tIntroduction: The Qurʾanic Miracle Stories: A Puzzling Motif? -- tPart 1. A Medieval Muslim Debate -- t1 In Defense of a Literal Reading of Miracles: Ghazali's Case for Contingency and Grace -- t2 A Cautious Approach to Miracle Stories: Ibn Rushd's Case for Rationalism and Divine Wisdom -- tPart 2. Reframing the Debate on Miracles in Modern Terms -- t3 David Hume on Empiricism, Common Sense, and Miracles -- t4 Charles S. Peirce on Pragmatism, Science, and Miracles -- tPart 3. Contemporary Connections -- t5 Said Nursi's Contemporary Reading of Qurʾanic Miracle Stories -- tConclusion: Qurʾanic Hermeneutics in the Modern Age -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aUnderstanding the Qurʾanic Miracle Stories in the Modern Age explores the ways in which meaningful implications have been drawn from stories of miracles in the Qurʾan. Isra Yazicioglu describes the fascinating medieval Muslim debate over miracles and connects its insights with early and late modern turning points in Western thought and with contemporary Qurʾanic interpretation. Building on an apparent tension within the Qurʾan and analyzing crucial cases of classical and modern Muslim engagement with these miracle stories, she illustrates how an apparent site of conflict between faith and reason, or revelation and science, can lead to fruitful exchange.A distinctive contribution to a new trend in Qurʾanic studies, this volume reveals the presence of insightful Qurʾanic interpretation outside of the traditional line-by-line commentary genre, engaging with the works of Ghazali, Ibn Rushd, and Said Nursi. Scholars of Islam, philosophy, and the intersection of science and religion will especially want to engage with Yazicioglu's study.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 7aPHILOSOPHY / Religious.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271062563423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271062563.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK